    {
      "title": "Active and Passive Participles",
      "titleArabic": "اسم الفاعل واسم المفعول",
      "content": [
        "The active participle (ism al-fā'il) describes the doer of an action, while the passive participle (ism al-maf'ūl) describes the recipient. Form IV has distinct patterns for both."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Active participle Form IV: مُفْعِل (muf'il)",
        "Passive participle Form IV: مُفْعَل (muf'al)",
        "Ḥijāzī mā can act like laysa (making the predicate manṣūb)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مُرْسِل", "english": "sender (active participle)" },
        { "arabic": "مُرْسَل", "english": "sent/messenger (passive participle)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Form IV Verbs (أَفْعَلَ)",
      "titleArabic": "باب أَفْعَلَ",
      "content": [
        "Form IV verbs are formed by prefixing hamza to the root and making the first radical sukūn. This pattern commonly makes intransitive verbs transitive or indicates causation."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Pattern: أَفْعَلَ (af'ala) with hamza prefix",
        "Maṣdar pattern: إِفْعَال (if'āl)",
        "Often causative: خَرَجَ (to go out) → أَخْرَجَ (to take out)",
        "Can indicate entering a state: صْبَحَ (morning) → أَصْبَحَ (to become/enter morning)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "أَرْسَلَ", "english": "to send" },
        { "arabic": "أَخْرَجَ", "english": "to take out / extract" },
        { "arabic": "أَسْلَمَ", "english": "to submit / become Muslim" }
      ]
    }
  ],
